WEBVTT

00:02.650 --> 00:04.490
<i>Previously on</i>
Fatal Attraction...

00:04.690 --> 00:06.180
- You should stay.
- I didn't think that this
is what we were doing.

00:06.380 --> 00:07.230
<i>- I'm sorry.</i>
<i>- ALEX: I can't let you pretend</i>

00:07.430 --> 00:08.660
<i>like I don't exist.</i>

00:08.860 --> 00:10.540
And I'm not going to be
ignored, Dan.

00:10.740 --> 00:12.410
<i>MIKE:</i>
<i>Why is she throwing acid</i>
<i>on your car?</i>

00:12.610 --> 00:13.890
I thought I had this handled,
then she shows up

00:14.090 --> 00:15.760
<i>in my fucking home.</i>

00:15.960 --> 00:17.890
- Hi.
<i>- DAN: I don't know what</i>
<i>you think you're doing,</i>

00:18.090 --> 00:20.070
- but it's going to stop.
- It's not going to st--
Why would it stop?

00:20.270 --> 00:22.330
I received an unofficial
complaint about Alex.

00:22.530 --> 00:23.900
Gabriel Ibarra. He had

00:24.100 --> 00:25.250
<i>rejected her.</i>
<i>She had backed off,</i>

00:25.450 --> 00:26.730
<i>but only sort of.</i>

00:26.930 --> 00:28.380
Earl's been working it
for six months,

00:28.580 --> 00:30.080
- and it's definitely a pattern.
- Against women.

00:30.280 --> 00:31.600
A pattern against women.

00:31.800 --> 00:34.170
Patterns are historically
Major Crimes Bureau.

00:34.370 --> 00:35.820
Because, "historically,"

00:36.020 --> 00:37.350
the Crimes Against Women Bureau
didn't exist.

00:37.550 --> 00:39.000
Gas and electric will be here.
When they leave,

00:39.200 --> 00:40.480
<i>you need to close the gate</i>
<i>and lock it.</i>

00:40.680 --> 00:43.000
<i>Then you may take Quincy out.</i>

00:43.200 --> 00:44.960
<i>DAN:</i>
<i>The gate was closed.</i>

00:45.160 --> 00:47.180
I just don't understand why
your mom would close the gate

00:47.380 --> 00:48.780
if she didn't know
where Quincy was.

00:50.130 --> 00:53.000
<i>DAN:</i>
<i>She was here.</i>

01:06.540 --> 01:08.240
MAN:
Let's wrap it up.

01:12.070 --> 01:14.460
[truck departing]

01:17.640 --> 01:19.390
[Quincy barks]

01:19.590 --> 01:21.960
Ah. Stay.

01:22.150 --> 01:23.220
SOPHIE:
Quincy, come.

01:23.420 --> 01:25.960
Oh... Oh.

01:26.160 --> 01:27.350
Who closed the gate?

01:27.550 --> 01:30.360
- Uh...
- Oh,

01:30.550 --> 01:32.230
thank Christ. Holy shit.

01:32.430 --> 01:34.450
If you hadn't,
that would've been it for me.

01:34.650 --> 01:36.750
It's the whole reason I'm here.

01:36.950 --> 01:38.410
And that dog
would've been gone forever,

01:38.610 --> 01:41.540
and my daughter would've
stuffed me down a storm drain.

01:41.740 --> 01:44.020
[laughs] Thank God for you. Wow.

01:44.220 --> 01:47.110
No, thank God,
thank God I saw him.

01:47.310 --> 01:48.850
I was just going to my house.

01:49.050 --> 01:52.380
The... blue colonial
with the-the porch.

01:52.580 --> 01:53.730
Huh.

01:53.930 --> 01:57.380
Uh, and I just, he was suddenly

01:57.580 --> 01:59.340
running towards me, and-and

01:59.540 --> 02:00.990
people drive so quickly
on this street.

02:01.190 --> 02:03.130
I'm-I'm just...
I'm glad I caught him.

02:03.330 --> 02:05.130
- I'm glad I didn't overstep.
- Oh, can I

02:05.330 --> 02:06.260
make you a...

02:06.460 --> 02:08.090
coffee of gratitude?

02:08.290 --> 02:11.660
Um, or-or do you have to go?

02:11.860 --> 02:13.790
Uh...

02:13.990 --> 02:17.710
No, I-I could use
a-a gratitude coffee.

02:17.910 --> 02:20.670
Great. Or maybe something
a little stronger.

02:20.870 --> 02:22.790
Or is that just me?

02:25.310 --> 02:28.890
No. No, it's not just you.

02:29.090 --> 02:32.320
Okay. [laughs]

02:37.280 --> 02:41.470
Your daughter's
a contractor, right?

02:41.670 --> 02:43.430
She-she has a business?

02:43.630 --> 02:45.950
With her best friend
from grad school, yeah.

02:46.150 --> 02:47.910
Sh-She's at work right now?

02:48.110 --> 02:49.480
No, actually, she and my husband

02:49.680 --> 02:51.780
went down to the antique mall
in Sherman Oaks.

02:51.980 --> 02:53.960
Oh.

02:54.160 --> 02:56.880
- Do you have any other children?
- No, just Bethie.

02:57.080 --> 02:58.100
When I got married,

02:58.290 --> 02:59.620
my mother told me she hoped

02:59.820 --> 03:01.620
I wasn't planning
to have children

03:01.820 --> 03:04.750
because she was worried I
wouldn't do well with maternity.

03:04.950 --> 03:07.670
Really? How old were you?

03:07.870 --> 03:09.320
I was just 20.

03:09.520 --> 03:11.720
You know, I hadn't really
thought about it, but

03:11.920 --> 03:14.850
then your mother tells you
you'd be a terrible mother,

03:15.050 --> 03:17.720
so, you know,
you take that on board.

03:17.920 --> 03:21.420
[laughs] So, I told my husband

03:21.620 --> 03:23.900
I don't want kids,
and he says, "Okay."

03:24.100 --> 03:25.820
But then, a few years went by,

03:26.020 --> 03:28.780
and, one day,
Warren came home, and I said,

03:28.980 --> 03:30.560
"What if we had a baby?

03:30.760 --> 03:33.830
What if, you know,
my mom was wrong about me?"

03:34.030 --> 03:36.000
And he just laughed. [laughs]

03:36.200 --> 03:37.960
He laughed and laughed.

03:38.160 --> 03:40.050
But was...

03:40.250 --> 03:41.530
Was she wrong?

03:41.730 --> 03:43.270
Well, I don't know.

03:43.470 --> 03:46.320
Maybe not about how terrible
a mother I was, but

03:46.520 --> 03:48.450
wrong about how much

03:48.650 --> 03:50.570
I was gonna love Bethie.

03:53.180 --> 03:54.670
- That's nice.
- Yeah.

03:54.870 --> 03:56.680
She and her father
are best friends.

03:56.870 --> 03:58.200
They're like the same person.

03:58.400 --> 04:01.590
I sometimes wonder,
if I just disappeared,

04:01.790 --> 04:03.030
how long it would
take them to notice

04:03.230 --> 04:06.080
I was gone. [laughs]

04:06.280 --> 04:08.600
You know,
Bethie designed this house.

04:08.800 --> 04:11.120
I mean, it's

04:11.320 --> 04:14.260
beautiful.
It's objectively beautiful.

04:14.460 --> 04:17.000
But all these bells
and whistles now,

04:17.200 --> 04:18.830
I-I just have to laugh.

04:19.030 --> 04:20.740
[voice fading]:
I mean, the-the dimmer switches

04:20.940 --> 04:22.960
and the butler pantry...

04:23.160 --> 04:24.790
[Sophie continues speaking
indistinctly]

04:24.990 --> 04:27.750
...water features.
They have this motorized

04:27.950 --> 04:29.190
pool cover.

04:29.390 --> 04:31.100
All they ever do is argue about

04:31.300 --> 04:33.970
whose turn it is to close it.

04:34.170 --> 04:36.450
- Whose turn is it?
- Who knows?

04:36.650 --> 04:39.670
It's a tale as old as time.

04:39.870 --> 04:42.550
[gasps] We should close it

04:42.750 --> 04:45.850
and let them each think
the other one did it.

04:46.050 --> 04:47.770
<i>Gift of the Magi.</i>

04:47.970 --> 04:51.080
Come with me. I never can figure
out how to work these things.

04:51.280 --> 04:53.770
I might need your wise counsel.

05:06.560 --> 05:07.880
[pool cover whirring]

05:08.080 --> 05:09.440
Oh, for the love of God,

05:09.640 --> 05:11.010
can you believe this? Look.

05:11.210 --> 05:12.750
All you have to do

05:12.950 --> 05:15.280
is literally
hold this button down.

05:15.480 --> 05:16.760
I mean...

05:16.950 --> 05:18.540
Oh, shit, I forgot that floatie.

05:18.740 --> 05:21.190
I probably need to get that
out of there, don't I?

05:21.390 --> 05:22.980
It's gonna make a big lump?

05:23.180 --> 05:24.940
I'll get it.

05:25.140 --> 05:26.970
[mutters]

05:28.580 --> 05:31.900
You know what? I should make us
some stuffed mushrooms.

05:32.100 --> 05:35.250
Oh, my God. They're just
those frozen ones, you know?

05:35.450 --> 05:36.950
[voice fading]:
From, uh, from whatsit?

05:37.150 --> 05:38.600
But, oh, they're amazing.

05:38.800 --> 05:40.770
Have you ever had them?

05:48.690 --> 05:50.790
[screams]

05:50.990 --> 05:51.920
[coughs]

05:52.120 --> 05:55.140
Oh, that was really silly.

05:55.340 --> 05:57.100
Ugh. Oh.

05:57.300 --> 05:59.360
- [coughs] Could you...
- [water splashing]

05:59.560 --> 06:00.970
Can you give me a hand?
I... [coughs]

06:01.170 --> 06:04.880
I'm not the best swimmer.
[coughing]

06:06.800 --> 06:08.500
Please!

06:08.700 --> 06:11.070
Can you... [labored breathing]
Can you hurry?

06:11.270 --> 06:13.770
Ugh. Wait. What are you doing?

06:13.970 --> 06:15.550
What are you doing?

06:15.750 --> 06:17.150
[screams]

06:18.200 --> 06:19.910
[water thrashing]

06:20.100 --> 06:22.590
[muffled screaming]

06:24.420 --> 06:25.820
[muffled coughing]

